cretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the performance of the Start Up Loan scheme in Wales to date; what the take-up has been under this scheme to date; and how much has been lent to which businesses in each constituency in Wales in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Alun Cairns","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","196696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48407","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p /> <p>Post Office Ltd, with its network of over 11,500 branches, is well placed to become a provider of front office services for Government, helping citizens interact with Government either face-to-face or online.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>While public services must be competitively tendered, Post Office Ltd has shown that it can very effectively bid for and win new work. It has won every Government contract it has bid for the past three years in highly competitive tendering processes.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>In particular, in 2012 it successfully bid for the competitively-tendered DVLA framework contract for Front Office Counter Services (FOCS). This contract runs to 2020 and is available to other Government departments. For example HM Passport Office recently moved its services with Post Office Ltd onto FOCS and this Department and the Cabinet Office are in close contact about a range of other opportunities.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Furthermore, Post Office Ltd was recently one of the successful bidders for the Cabinet Office's online identity assurance contract, ensuring that Post Office Ltd can play a role in the delivery of modern, online Government services.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Whilst I continue to highlight to my colleagues the opportunities available to Government from using the Post Office network and contracts such as these, individual contracts are a matter for the services in question and their respective public bodies and departments. I have not had recent discussions specifically with the Welsh Government.</p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48407/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48407/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on increasing the range of services provided by the Post Office network.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48408","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>Post Office Ltd, with its network of over 11,500 branches, is well placed to become a provider of front office services for Government, helping citizens interact with Government either face-to-face or online.</p><p> </p><p>While public services must be competitively tendered, Post Office Ltd has shown that it can very effectively bid for and win new work. It has won every Government contract it has bid for the past three years in highly competitive tendering processes.</p><p> </p><p>In particular, in 2012 it successfully bid for the competitively-tendered DVLA framework contract for Front Office Counter Services (FOCS). This contract runs to 2020 and is available to other Government departments. For example HM Passport Office recently moved its services with Post Office Ltd onto FOCS and this Department and the Cabinet Office are in close contact about a range of other opportunities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, Post Office Ltd was recently one of the successful bidders for the Cabinet Office's online identity assurance contract, ensuring that Post Office Ltd can play a role in the delivery of modern, online Government services.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst I continue to highlight to my colleagues the opportunities available to Government from using the Post Office network and contracts such as these, individual contracts are a matter for the services in question and their respective public bodies and departments. I have not had recent discussions specifically with the Northern Ireland Executive.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48408/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48408/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on increasing the range of services provided by the Post Office network.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48409","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>Provisional student numbers for 2014/15 were issued on 20 February 2014. Since then we have considered applications for a higher number and adjusted numbers issued where appropriate on 2 May 2014. However, we cannot confirm final allocations until providers have been re-designated for student support purposes for the 2014/15 academic year.</p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48409/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48409/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to announce the final allocation of student number controls to alternative providers.","false","Biography information for Mr Nick Raynsford","Greenwich and Woolwich","Mr Nick Raynsford","196560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48410","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The Supplementary Estimate adjustment for the student loan debt sale relates to the Government subsidising the sale of student loans in 1998 and 1999. The adjustment reflects changes to the value of the Government liability following annual debt sale subsidy payments, including adjustments for cancelled loans.</p><p> </p><p>The subsidy will continue until all the loans are extinguished which is expected to be no earlier than 2028, which is the 30 year duration of the first debt sale agreement.</p><p> </p><p>Further details of the liability are available in the BIS Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48410/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48410/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to page 204 of HM Treasury's Central Government and Supply Estimates 2013-14, February 2014, HC 1006, if he will provide a breakdown of the £15.877 million supplementary estimate for the increase in costs of student loan debt sale.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","196546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48411","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) publishes data on the sources of income for all higher education institutions (HEIs) in the UK on an annual basis. This data shows that, despite a slight fall in student numbers, tuition fee income from non-EU students in 2012-13 was £3.5bn, an increase of 9.1% on 2011-12.</p><p> </p><p>The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) produces an annual report on the financial health of the publicly funded higher education sector in England. Their most recent report, published in March 2014, also states that income from non-EU students rose in 2012-13 and shows that HEIs are expecting tuition fee income from non-EU students to rise by 9.7% in real terms in 2013-14.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent HEFCE report can be found at <a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/pubs/2014/201402/HEFCE2014_02.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/hefce/content/pubs/2014/201402/HEFCE2014_02.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48411/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48411/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential financial effect on UK higher education institutions of the reduction in non-EU students in 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","196536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48412","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>A wide variety of public sources frequently make comparative assessment of international Apprenticeships systems.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48412/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48412/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will undertake a comparative assessment of Government spending on apprenticeships in the UK and Germany.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48413","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>No decision has been made on the payment of this discretionary payment.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48413/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48413/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 9 April 2014, Official Report, column 291W, on Royal Mail, for what reasons the underwriters' discretionary fee has not been paid.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","196537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48414","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The funding available for adult further education and skills in 2013-14 financial year was £4.1bn of which £3.6bn was routed through the Skills Funding Agency to support the capacity for 3 million learners. More detailed data on spend in that financial year are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>The funding available for apprenticeships in 2013-14 financial year was £1,566m of which £802m was provided by the Department for Education for those aged 16-18 and £764m was provided by the Department for Business Innovation and Skills for those aged 19 and over. More detailed data on spend in that financial year are not yet available.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","196540","2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48414/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48414/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what amount the Government spent on full-time students in technical colleges in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48415","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The funding available for adult further education and skills in 2013-14 financial year was £4.1bn of which £3.6bn was routed through the Skills Funding Agency to support the capacity for 3 million learners. More detailed data on spend in that financial year are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>The funding available for apprenticeships in 2013-14 financial year was £1,566m of which £802m was provided by the Department for Education for those aged 16-18 and £764m was provided by the Department for Business Innovation and Skills for those aged 19 and over. More detailed data on spend in that financial year are not yet available.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","196539","2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48415/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48415/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what amount his Department spent on all apprenticeships in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48416","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The legislation relating to official receivers and Insolvency Service technical staff, does not require study to hold an Insolvency Practitioners' Licence and, as such, no staff will receive training that will lead to either a personal insolvency partial licence or a corporate insolvency partial licence.</p><p> </p><p><em>Under S399(1) of the Insolvency Act 1986 “………the official receiver, in relation to any bankruptcy, </em><em>winding up</em><em>, individual voluntary arrangement, debt relief order or application for such an order</em><em>is any person who by virtue of the following provisions ………….is authorised to act as the official receiver ………..” and S399(2) “The Secretary of State may ……. appoint persons to the office of official receiver ……………….”.</em></p><p><em> </em></p><p>All technical staff are required to study for, and pass, a bespoke accredited training programme at Qualifications &amp; Credit Framework Level 3 and are required to undertake a minimum of 5 days Continuous Professional Development per year.</p><p>Incidentally, over 50% of Official Receivers hold a professional qualification e.g. ACCA.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48416/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48416/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the proportion of (a) Official Receivers and (b) all Insolvency Service officials who will receive training leading to a (i) personal insolvency partial licence and (ii) corporate insolvency partial licence.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","196532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48417","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The exact number of agency workers in the UK who are employed on pay between assignment contracts is not known. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills continues to monitor available evidence and is talking to relevant stakeholders to gather further information about the effects of pay between assignments contracts.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48417/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48417/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will undertake an assessment of the effects that pay between assignment contracts have on agency workers' pay.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48418","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-04-30","<p>Higher apprenticeship starts in Lancashire Local Education Authority have increased from 40 in the 2009/10 academic year to 370 in 2012/13.</p><p> </p><p>The Budget announced £20 million over 2014-15 and 2015-16 for new support for employer investment in apprenticeships in England up to postgraduate level, which will provide apprentices with the technical skills that employers need. This will complement the £80 million funding over 2014-15 and 2015-16 for 20,000 more higher apprenticeships announced in the autumn statement – more than doubling current volumes.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48418/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48418/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of higher apprenticeships in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","196486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48419","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>Full-time undergraduate student support expenditure by the Student Loans Company for the 2013-14 financial year included £8.9bn of cash outlay on maintenance and fee loans and £1.9bn of grant expenditure (on maintenance grants and other allowances). These totals include expenditure on English-domiciled students in the UK and EU students in England.</p><p> </p><p>For the financial year 2013-14, the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) estimate that £2.1bn of the expenditure set out in the 2014 grant letter refers to teaching grant for full-time undergraduate study. It is not possible to calculate a full-time undergraduate share of every element of recurrent teaching grant such as Senior Professional pay, teaching strategy funding, institution-specific initiatives or additional funding for Equivalent Level Qualifications and vulnerable science subjects.</p><p> </p><p>The figures do not include expenditure by other Governments departments.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48419/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48419/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Government spent on full-time university education for undergraduates in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48420","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>There are no proposals for change to the relevant legislation on agency workers at EU level at this stage.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48420/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48420/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will support the introduction of legislation at EU level to ensure that pay between assignment contracts does not result in agency workers being paid a lower wage than other employees.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","196534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48421","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The Government's International Education Strategy, published in July 2013, included an analysis of the value of international students to the UK. Expenditure on tuition fees and living expenses were shown to be the two largest components of UK higher education (HE) exports. The international education strategy can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity</a></p><p> </p><p>More recent data for the 2012/13 academic year is now available. The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) publishes data on the sources of income for all higher education institutions (HEIs) in the UK on an annual basis. In 2012/13 tuition fee income from non-EU students at UK HEIs was £3.5bn.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, BIS has estimated that living expenses of non-EU students was £4.3bn in 2012/13. Some of this expenditure is likely to flow to HEIs (e.g. via accommodation services)</p><p> </p><p>International students also bring indirect economic benefits to the HE sector, including strengthening the quality, diversity and reputation of the sector and improving overseas business, research, social and cultural links.</p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48421/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48421/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he made of the total financial contribution made by non-EU students to the UK's higher education sector.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","196535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48422","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The Working Time Regulations entitle all workers in the UK to 5.6 weeks paid annual leave. This is an important right, and evidence suggests that the number of employees not taking it is very small. Labour Force Survey analysis shows that the vast majority of workers (95 per cent) report receiving their entitlement to paid leave. Similarly the 4<sup>th</sup> Work Life Balance Employees survey indicates that 93 per cent of employees receive their full statutory annual leave entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>Statutory holiday entitlement can be calculated online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/calculate-your-holiday-entitlement" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/calculate-your-holiday-entitlement</a></p><p> </p><p>Workers who think they may not be receiving their full statutory entitlement should contact the Pay and Work Rights Helpline on 0800 917 2368, or ACAS (<a href="http://www.acas.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.acas.org.uk</a>) for free and confidential advice.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48422/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48422/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the level of denial of paid statutory holiday entitlement in the workplace; and what steps he is taking to tackle such a refusal of statutory rights.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","196508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48423","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The announced changes to Disabled Students' Allowances (DSAs) will be subject to a full equality analysis to determine the impact of these changes on students with protected characteristics. The equality analysis will be given full consideration before regulations are laid before the House.</p><p> </p><p>These changes will apply to all full-time, full-time distance learning, part-time and postgraduate students in higher education applying for DSA for the first time from the 2015/16 academic year. DSAs are not available to further education students, as the Government provides Learning Support funding to further education colleges and providers to help meet the additional needs of learners with learning difficulties and/or disabilities.</p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts","196612","2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48423/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48423/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of changes to disabled students' allowances on the number of disabled students completing higher or further education.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","196514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48424","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>Following the Chancellor's announcement in the 2014 Budget UK Export Finance formally launched the Export Refinancing Facility (ERF) on 30 April 2014.</p><p> </p><p>ERF is aimed at supporting UK bids for projects that require finance above $150m. As these projects typically involve lengthy contract negotiations, it may be sometime before we see a pipeline of deals that benefit from the ERF.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48424/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48424/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many businesses received support through the UK Guarantees Exports Refinancing Facility in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","196716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48425","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-04-30","<p>The National Careers Service marketing strategy using targeted on-line activity has been pursued since October 2013.</p><p> </p><p>Through regular market research we have seen an increase in awareness[1] of the support the National Careers Service offers since the campaign started from 24 per cent to 29 per cent. All of the targeted groups show a greater awareness than the remainder of those sampled:</p><p> </p><p>· Awareness among individuals looking to advance their career has increased by 28 per cent increase to 39 per cent;</p><p>· Awareness among those who are looking for a better job to support a change in circumstances has increased by 14 per cent to 32 per cent;</p><p>· Awareness among those who have been or are about to be made redundant has remained broadly the same with 37 per cent aware of the Service.</p><p> </p><p>Over 56 per cent of these three groups are likely to use the Service, compared with only 8 per cent of others surveyed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><br /><p>[1] Both spontaneous and prompted.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48425/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48425/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 April 2014, Official Report, column 744W, on National Careers Service, what assessment his Department has made of the National Careers Service's progress in achieving its key strategic aims for marketing.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","196641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48426","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-08","<p>We hope to publish the Government response before Summer. Any legislative changes we decide to make will be taken forward when Parliamentary time permits.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-08T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48426/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48426/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when his Department plans to publish its response to the consultation on Streamlining Regulatory and Competition Appeals launched in June 2013; and on what timetable he intends to introduce reforms arising from that consultation.","false","Biography information for Alun Cairns","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","196719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48427","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>The cost of the review primarily relates to the salary costs of review team members, who undertook the review as a corporate objective alongside their existing responsibilities. On average, the review team spent around 10% of their weekly core work hours on the review across its duration. There were additional costs associated with the extensive stakeholder engagement and in year awards to review team members to recognise their personal contribution in completing the review. These awards are consistent with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills' (BIS) In-Year Awards policy of recognising and rewarding contributions to business performance and demonstrating the BIS values.</p><p> </p><p>The estimated maximum total cost to BIS of the review team is £81,350, which represents 0.002% of total Research Council funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48427/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48427/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the cost was of the recent triennial review of the Research Councils.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","196730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48428","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-06","<p>I have no plans to end the Department's check-off arrangements.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48428/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48428/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has any plans to end the employee trade union membership dues check-off system.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48429","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-29","<p>As was the case under the previous administration, details of internal meetings are not normally published.</p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</a>.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-04-29T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48429/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48429/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings his Department has had for which the check off system of paying trade union fees was on the agenda.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48430","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-05-06","<p>The issue of voting in domestic elections is a matter for national governments and we do not accept the Commission's view of a European Public Space.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48430/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48430/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48430/answer/previousversion/8078","Biography information for Greg Clark","58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what steps he is taking in support of Action 12 of the EU Citizenship Report 2013, com (2013) 269.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","196654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48431","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. However, as part of this Government's commitment to reducing waste and driving down costs, we are challenging departments on the need to make savings from facilities management.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48431/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48431/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will estimate how much Government departments have spent on filtering tap water for drinking in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","196664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48432","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>The Emergency Planning College (EPC) has had no requests for direct support of the planning and preparation for the Giro D'Italia Big Start in Northern Ireland in May 2014. The EPC has however delivered a variety of civil protection and resilience planning courses in Northern Ireland for various organisations, including Sports NI.</p><p>The Emergency Planning College (EPC) has provided 79 courses on emergency planning and crises management courses to 1170 attendees delivered in Northern Ireland since 2006. In addition to the training provided for customer organisations in NI, the EPC has trained 358 practitioners from NI attending residential training courses at the EPC since 2006</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","196574","2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48432/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48432/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what support the Emergency Planning College has provided to the planning and preparation for the Giro D'Italia Big Start in Northern Ireland in May 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","196661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48433","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>The Emergency Planning College (EPC) has had no requests for direct support of the planning and preparation for the Giro D'Italia Big Start in Northern Ireland in May 2014. The EPC has however delivered a variety of civil protection and resilience planning courses in Northern Ireland for various organisations, including Sports NI.</p><p>The Emergency Planning College (EPC) has provided 79 courses on emergency planning and crises management courses to 1170 attendees delivered in Northern Ireland since 2006. In addition to the training provided for customer organisations in NI, the EPC has trained 358 practitioners from NI attending residential training courses at the EPC since 2006</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","196661","2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48433/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48433/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many training courses the Emergency Planning College has provided in Northern Ireland in each year since the college was established; and how many people from Northern Ireland have completed such training courses.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","196574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48434","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Leicester South on 2 April 2014 (Official Report) Column Ref: 721W.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48434/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48434/answer","PQ196760 - Referral.docx","Referral Answer for Member","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48434/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has any plans to end the employee trade union membership dues check-off system.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48435","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>Since January 2011, as part of the Government's transparency programme, details of contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a></p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48435/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48435/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many contracts the Government holds with (a) Johnson & Johnson, (b) Ethicon and (c) BARD; and what the value was of contracts with each such company.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48436","Cabinet Office","false","2014-04-30","<p>As was the case under the previous administration, The Government expects all holders of public office to work to the highest personal and professional standards. As set out in the Code of Conduct for Board Members of Public Bodies, public appointees are expected to uphold the standards of conduct set out in the Committee on Standards in Public Life's Seven Principles of Public Life.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48436/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48436/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what background checks are regularly made on appointees to quasi-autonomous non-governmental organisations.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","196791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48437","Cabinet Office","false","2014-05-06","<p>Appointments and promotion in the Civil Service should be made on merit through fair and open competition. To ensure our civil service delivers the best for Britain we must draw on the widest possible pool of talent. We want to ensure that the best people - irrespective of who they are - rise to the top of the Civil Service but are concerned that for too long the very top ranks do not reflect those further down. We have commissioned independent research to look at the blockages women face making it to the very top and will use this to drive a new strategy for managing talent.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48437/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48437/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the Government's target is for the proportion of (a) women, (b) people from black and minority ethnic communities and (c) disabled people in senior management posts in central government departments.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","196793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48438","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-06","<p>In HM Treasury these arrangements are kept under review.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48438/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48438/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has any plans to end the employee trade union membership dues check-off system.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48439","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-06","<p>No reliable estimate has been possible for the value of VAT levied on the sale of e-books purchased in 2012‑13 and 2013-14.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48439/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48439/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much HM Treasury received in VAT charged on ebooks in (a) 2012-13 and (b) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","196595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48440","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-06","<p>Raising the income tax personal allowance to £12,300 in 2015-16 is estimated to cost in the region of £9.5 billion.</p><p> </p><p>A reduction to the basic rate limit has been assumed so that the higher rate threshold is unchanged. As a result of this, basic rate and most higher rate taxpayers would benefit equally from the personal allowance increase.</p><p> </p><p>This estimate is based on the 2011-12 Survey of Personal Incomes, projected to 2015-16 using economic assumptions consistent with the Office for Budget Responsibility's March 2014 economic and fiscal outlook.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48440/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48440/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the potential cost to the public purse of raising the income tax personal allowance for 2015-16 from £10,500 to £12,300 with the same maximum cash benefit going to basic and higher rate taxpayers but no benefit going to additional rate taxpayers.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","196610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48441","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-06","<p><strong>The Government and Northern Ireland Executive have taken forward a constructive and positive programme of work examining the potential for devolving corporation tax powers to the Northern Ireland Assembly.</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>As agreed in “Building a prosperous and united community” the Government is taking forward further work on corporation tax devolution and will make a final decision on the devolution of these powers no later than the Autumn Statement 2014.</strong></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48441/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48441/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he last discussed the possible devolution of corporation tax with the Northern Ireland Executive.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","196577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48442","HM Treasury","false","2014-04-30","<p><strong>As set out at Autumn Statement 2012, </strong><strong>the Government will wait for further progress on planned operational changes to the tax system before formally consulting on the operational integration of income tax and NICs.</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</strong></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a></strong></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48442/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48442/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had on combining national insurance and income tax.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","196602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48443","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-06","<p>Raising the National Insurance Contributions thresholds for individual earners (The Primary Threshold and Lower Profits Limit) in 2015-16 to £10,000 is estimated to cost in the region of £5 billion. Raising them to £12,300 is estimated to cost around £10.5 billion.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are based on the 2011-12 Survey of Personal Incomes, projected to 2015-16 using economic assumptions consistent with the Office for Budget Responsibility's March 2014 economic and fiscal outlook.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48443/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48443/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the potential cost to the public purse of raising the national insurance personal allowance for 2015-16 to (a) £10,000 and (b) £12,300.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","196603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48444","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-01","<p>This question has been taken as asking about fines related to non-payment of the NMW.</p><p> </p><p>The Government takes the enforcement of NMW very seriously and HMRC enforce the national minimum wage legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does that by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, in addition to carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to 6 April 2009, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) issued penalty notices to those employers who failed to comply, within 28 days, with an enforcement notice. A new enforcement regime, introduced in April 2009, saw the introduction of automatic penalties for employers who are found to have underpaid their workers.</p><p>The number and value of penalties issued to Northern Ireland employers for the calendar years 2010-14 is set out in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Value</p></td><td><p>£33,635</p></td><td><p>£49,135</p></td><td><p>£41,110</p></td><td><p>£40,724</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-05-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48444/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48444/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many fines of what total value have been imposed by HM Revenue and Customs on employers in Northern Ireland in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012 and (d) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","196656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48445","HM Treasury","false","2014-04-30","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of National Minimum Wage (NMW) very seriously and HMRC enforce the NMW legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does that by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, in addition carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has an NMW enforcement team based in Belfast, and that team investigates all complaints received by the Pay &amp; Work Rights Helpline relating to Northern Ireland based employers alongside employers who are based and trading in the wider UK. The NMW Belfast team works closely with other Northern Ireland enforcement agencies including the Gangmasters Licensing Authority, Home Office Immigration &amp; Enforcement and Department of Employment and Learning.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48445/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48445/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps HM Revenue and Customs is taking to tackle cases of employees in Northern Ireland being paid below the minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","196655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48446","HM Treasury","false","2014-04-30","<p><strong>As shown in HMRC's published statistics (Table PEN3 available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/259967/pen3.pdf), in 2011-12 around 20,000 unemployed adults made or received contributions into their personal pensions. 6,000 of these individuals made use of the non-earnings pension contribution limit of £3,600 including basic rate tax relief. </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>A further 10,000 children, 10,000 individuals in full time education and 10,000 carers made or received contributions into their personal pensions. Of these, around a quarter made use of the non-earnings pension contribution limit. </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Of the individuals mentioned above who made use of the non-earnings pension contribution limit in 2011-12, around two thirds were female.</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>The Government has made no assessment of the effects of increasing the limit on couples saving together for retirement but keeps all tax policies under review.</strong></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48446/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48446/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of men and women who make use of the non-earnings pension contribution limit; and if he will assess the potential effects of increasing that limit on couples saving together for retirement.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","196630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48447","HM Treasury","false","2014-04-30","<p>The Simplified Import VAT Accounting (SIVA) scheme is a trade facilitation measure that reduces compliance costs for legitimate traders through the removal of the requirement to provide a guarantee to secure import VAT paid through the duty deferment scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The risk to the tax revenue by traders operating SIVA is potentially very large as the period between the tax due being deferred and being collected by HMRC may result in a failure to pay. The setting of the SIVA approval criteria has to strike a balance between ensuring the trade receive the maximum benefit from the scheme, while at the same time protecting the revenue.</p><p> </p><p>Businesses have to demonstrate on-going compliance with the SIVA requirements. The SIVA team monitor this through internal systems, including any outstanding debts or Time-to Pay agreements requested. When they identify a business experiencing difficulties, they advise them of the potential impact on their SIVA approval. Warning letters are issued by the team to businesses who fail to comply and only if there is evidence of continued non-compliance is the approval removed.</p><p>The current procedures provide an appropriate balance between trade faciliation and protection of the revenue.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48447/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48447/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to improve support for small and medium-sized enterprises which are in need of short-term assistance and flexibility through improved partnership working between the HM Revenue and Custom's (HMRC) simplified import VAT accounting duty deferment team and the HMRC debt management and time-to-pay teams; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","196640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48448","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-01","<p>The UK is at the forefront of global efforts to tackle excessive pay in the financial sector and ensure that pay is aligned with performance; our tough Remuneration Code requires deferral of at least 60% of bonuses of senior bankers and limits the amounts that can be paid in cash. Bonuses are down significantly since their peak under the last Government, and are now largely deferred and paid in shares.</p><p> </p><p>In contrast, the EU's bonus cap is a poorly thought through measure that undermines rather than reinforces our efforts by pushing up fixed pay. It was introduced without any proper impact assessment and has serious issues around its compatibility with the EU Treaty, and for these reasons we are challenging it in the European Court of Justice. However, pending the outcome, the Government is fully implementing the cap in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Prudential Regulation Authority and Financial Conduct Authority have responsibility for ensuring that remuneration practices in the banking sector are compliant with the new rules.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-05-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48448/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48448/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the prevalence of allowances being paid to senior bank executives to enable them to avoid the EU bonus cap.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","196644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48449","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-13","<p> </p><p>The Department is undertaking a wider evaluation of the New Homes Bonus; its findings will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-05-13T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48449/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48449/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects to publish the findings of the research he commissioned from the University of Sheffield into the New Homes Bonus.","true","Biography information for Mr Nick Raynsford","Greenwich and Woolwich","Mr Nick Raynsford","196708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48450","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-05-01","<p> </p><p /> <p>The detail requested is not held centrally by this Department, however the Annual Report to Parliament published in January this year indicated our estimate of static library closures in England since the beginning of 2010, is around 90. While the number of public libraries has reduced there has been a notable growth in the number of libraries managed or run by the community. The Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy (CIPFA) collect, annually, from the individual library authorities, public library statistics which contain information relating to the net figure of public libraries open in each year, as well as the number and type of libraries and the average hours of opening per week. This shows the number of library service points open 10+ hours per week in England (incl. mobiles) at 31 March 2013 was 3,181. However, CIPFA do not collect data on the number of library closures or those that have reduced their opening hours. Copies of CIPFA statistics are available in the libraries of both Houses.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-05-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48450/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48450/answer","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48450/answer/previousversion/8074","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many libraries in Greater London have (a) closed and (b) reduced opening hours since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","196693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48451","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>Statistics on the amount of dwelling stock in England by tenure are published in the Department's live table 104, which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p>This provides the total amount of stock owned by Private Registered Providers (housing associations) and local authorities but does not provide any further breakdown.</p><p>More detailed information on housing stock owned by local authorities, including a breakdown between those for social rent and those for affordable rent, for 2011-12 and 2012-13 only, can be found in the dataset that accompanies the Department's annual Local Authority Housing Statistics release. Information on housing stock for intermediate rent and affordable home ownership is not collected separately. For 2011-12 and 2012-13, these datasets can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2012-to-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2012-to-2013</a> (Section A, Question 2)</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2011-to-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2011-to-2012</a> (Section A, Question 2)</p><p>Detailed information on housing stock owned by Private Registered Providers can be found in the dataset that accompanies the Homes and Communities Agency's annual Statistical Data Return. For 2011-12 and 2012-13, these datasets can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/news/second-statistical-data-return" target="_blank">http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/news/second-statistical-data-return</a> (2012-13)</p><p><a href="http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/news/statistical-data-return" target="_blank">http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/news/statistical-data-return</a> (2011-12)</p><p>Prior to 2011-12, this information was collected in the Tenant Services Authority's Regulatory and Statistical return and can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120419011320/http:/www.tenantservicesauthority.org/server/show/nav.15039" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120419011320/http://www.tenantservicesauthority.org/server/show/nav.15039</a></p><p>£19.5 billion of public and private investment in affordable homes will deliver 170,000 homes in the four years to 2015. Half way through, we have already delivered almost 99,000 affordable homes (98,700).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48451/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48451/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much housing stock was held by (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations for (i) social rent, (ii) affordable rent, (iii) intermediate rent and (iv) affordable homeownership in each year from 2010 to 2013.","true","Biography information for Mr Nick Raynsford","Greenwich and Woolwich","Mr Nick Raynsford","196529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48452","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>The numbers of lead tenants being given social housing aged under 18 in England in the past five years for which data are available (1<sup>st</sup> April 2008 – 31<sup>st</sup> March 2013) is in the table below. Lead tenants are defined as the most economically active in the household. Numbers shown include lettings from both local authorities and private registered providers.</p><p>The numbers per year and per tenure type are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Tenant age</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008/09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12<sup>i,ii</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13<sup>i,ii</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>General Needs</p></td><td><p>Under 18</p></td><td><p>2,758</p></td><td><p>2,232</p></td><td><p>2,108</p></td><td><p>1,875</p></td><td><p>1,535</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>of which under 16</em></p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total lettings</p></td><td><p>264,790</p></td><td><p>260,235</p></td><td><p>269,187</p></td><td><p>270,678</p></td><td><p>260,530</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>Supported Housing<sup>iii</sup></p></td><td><p>Under 18</p></td><td><p>9,579</p></td><td><p>8,520</p></td><td><p>9,384</p></td><td><p>9,021</p></td><td><p>7,989</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>of which under 16</em></p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total lettings</p></td><td><p>114,400</p></td><td><p>107,520</p></td><td><p>124,438</p></td><td><p>123,806</p></td><td><p>118,213</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>Under 18</p></td><td><p>12,336</p></td><td><p>10,752</p></td><td><p>11,492</p></td><td><p>10,897</p></td><td><p>9,524</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>of which under 16</em></p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total lettings</p></td><td><p>379,190</p></td><td><p>367,756</p></td><td><p>393,625</p></td><td><p>394,484</p></td><td><p>378,743</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>i. Includes both social and Affordable Rent lettings.</p><p>ii. For 2011/12 and 2012/13, age is imputed where missing.</p><p>iii. Supported housing is defined as housing with special design facilities features, or designated for a particular client group.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note: values in columns may not sum to totals due to rounding. Source: Continuous Recording of Lettings system (CORE).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48452/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48452/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people (a) under 18 and (b) under 16 years of age have been given social housing in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","196482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48453","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p><em>[Holding Reply: Wednesday 30 April 2014]</em></p><p>I refer the right hon. Member to my answer of 21 November 2013, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 980-981W and my answer to him of 16 December 2013, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 443-444W.</p><p>I also refer him to the Written Ministerial Statement by my rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State (Eric Pickles) of 28 April 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 35WS, which outlines the rationale for the steps taken on 17 April, and how we are prepared to take further action against other breaches of the Publicity Code.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48453/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48453/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48453/answer/previousversion/8058","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities publish magazines or newsletters more than four times a year.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","196666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48454","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-09","<p> </p><p><em>[Holding Reply: Thursday 1 May 2014]</em></p><p>Spending power figures by local authority are published as part of the Local Government Finance Settlement, which is laid before the House each year. This information is also reasonably accessible to the hon. Member on my Department's website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/final-local-government-finance-settlement-england-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/final-local-government-finance-settlement-england-2014-to-2015</a> (2014-15 and provisional 2015-16)</p><p><a href="http://www.local.communities.gov.uk/finance/1314/settle.htm" target="_blank">www.local.communities.gov.uk/finance/1314/settle.htm</a> (2013-14)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-05-09T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48454/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48454/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48454/answer/previousversion/8250","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the spending power is for (a) Wokingham Council and (b) Newcastle upon Tyne City Council in (i) 2013-14, (ii) 2014-15 and (iii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Andy Sawford","Corby","Andy Sawford","196704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48455","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>At the Autumn Statement we announced a £1 billion package of business rates support to help shops and local firms. This included a £1,000 discount for two years for smaller shops, pubs and restaurants. Based on local authority reports of the amount of relief awarded, we estimate that 272,300 properties will benefit in England, including 7,740 in Lancashire.</p><p>The support package also included a 50 per cent discount for businesses taking on long-term empty shops, the doubling of small business rate relief for another year, a 2% cap on RPI increases for 2014-2015, allowing businesses to spread their business rates payments over 12 months, and allowing ratepayers that take on a second property to keep their small business rate relief for an extra year.</p><p>The Localism Act has also made it easier for small firms to claim small business rate relief.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48455/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48455/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to help local shops in (a) England and (b) Lancashire with the cost of business rates.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","196542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48456","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>My Department has received a number of recent representations from individual housing association tenants to extend the Right to Acquire to homes built before 1997, to enable them to buy the home in which they currently live.</p><p>The Right to Acquire is offered on a different basis to the Right to Buy, including the level of discount, to reflect the different tenancy and type of landlord. Housing association properties which were not part of a stock transfer have been provided through various forms of finance, including private money. However, the Government is committed to keeping the policy under review and we are open to further representations on this matter.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48456/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48456/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent representations he has received on the potential merits of extending the Right to Acquire to homes built before 1997.","false","Biography information for Mary Macleod","Brentford and Isleworth","Mary Macleod","196563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48457","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>As set out in my answer to the hon. Member for Croydon North (Steve Reed) on 2 December 2013, <em>Official Report</em>, column 556W, the criteria used by local authorities to determine whether a family is deemed turned around are published in the Financial Framework for the Troubled Families Programme's Payment by Results Scheme. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-troubled-families-programme-financial-framework" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-troubled-families-programme-financial-framework</a></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48457/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48457/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2014, Official Report, column 56W, on families: disadvantaged, what criteria his Department uses for assessing whether a family has been turned around.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","196545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48458","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>The Localism Act 2011 has strengthened the role of Local Plans and abolished the last Administration's top-down Regional Strategies. Our streamlined National Planning Policy Framework strongly encourages areas to get up-to-date Local Plans in place, and we have been actively supporting councils in doing so. Local Plans now set the framework in which decisions on particular applications are taken, whether locally or at appeal, unless material considerations indicate otherwise.</p><p>The Brighton and Hove Local Plan is currently at examination before an independent Inspector and it would not be appropriate for me to comment on the content of the Plan. However, I understand that the Inspector has agreed a programme of additional work with Brighton and Hove Council.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48458/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48458/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with Brighton and Hove City Council on the finalisation of the City Plan for the area; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","196617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48459","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework asks local planning authorities to assess the full housing requirements in their area and plan for a mix of housing based on demographic trends and the needs of different groups in the area, including students.</p><p>The recently published planning guidance confirms that: ‘All student accommodation, whether it consists of communal halls of residence or self-contained dwellings, and whether or not it is on campus, can be included towards the housing requirement, based on the amount of accommodation it releases in the housing market. Notwithstanding, local authorities should take steps to avoid double-counting'.</p><p>The relevant planning guidance, paragraph 39, can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/housing-and-economic-land-availability-assessment/stage-5-final-evidence-base/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/housing-and-economic-land-availability-assessment/stage-5-final-evidence-base/</a></p><p>Student accommodation is also eligible for the New Homes Bonus. Our approach reflects the fact that increases in dedicated student accommodation has a beneficial effect on wider housing supply, by taking pressure off private rented accommodation.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48459/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48459/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance he has given on whether (a) student housing need should be contained within local authority housing targets and (b) proposed student accommodation should be counted towards Local Plan housing numbers.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","196618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48460","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-05-06","<p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework sets out our policies for the conservation and enhancement of the natural environment. The biodiversity, ecosystems and green infrastructure section of our new web-based planning guidance explains how these matters should be taken into account in the planning system. Defra is consulting on a National Pollinator Strategy and my officials are working with Defra officials.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48460/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48460/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that measures to protect bees and other pollinators are fully reflected in planning practice guidance.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Roberta Blackman-Woods","196786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48461","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-04-30","<p> </p><p>Statistics on the amount of dwelling stock in England by tenure are published in the Department's live table 104, which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p>Taken together, the Private Registered Provider (housing association) and local authority tenures provide an estimate of total social housing.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-04-30T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48461/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48461/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the net change was in the number of homes for social rent between 1984 and 1990.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","196794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48462","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-05-06","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport has not made any specific assessment of the adequacy of emergency telephone coverage in the West Lothian local authority area. However, the Department and the independent national telecommunications regulator (Ofcom) work closely with all the Scottish emergency services and communications providers on matters such as this through the Government's 999/112 Liaison Committee. All the Scottish emergency services have been key contributors both in discussions on next generation access to 999 and in reviewing the code of practice that defines how emergency services and telecommunications providers work together.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48462/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48462/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of emergency telephone coverage in West Lothian local authority area.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48463","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-05-06","<p>Check-off is a matter delegated to Departments and it is for them to determine the appropriateness of continuing with the current arrangements. DCMS is in the process of reviewing its current arrangements for provision of check-off.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-05-06T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48463/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48463/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has any plans to end the employee trade union membership dues check-off system.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","196761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48464","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-05-08","<p>No such assessment has been made. Ministers are currently considering the responses received to the consultation. They will then decide the scope and extent of proposals to be implemented.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-05-08T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48464/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/48464/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-04-25",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect on industry of delays in the implementation of the Government's proposals to streamline regulatory and competition appeals.","false","Biography information for Alun Cairns","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","196698"
